    "narrative_summary": "The ATM c.829G>T (p.Glu277Ter) variant creates a premature stop codon in exon 7 of the ATM gene, truncating the protein and abolishing its kinase activity. It has been reported in patients with the autosomal\u2011recessive disorder ataxia\u2011telangiectasia (A\u2011T) and in several cancer\u2011predisposition contexts.\nClinical observations consistently describe the allele as disease\u2011causing. A homozygous stop\u2011gain was identified in an Iranian A\u2011T patient and classified as pathogenic after Sanger confirmation and structural modelling [32962506]. The same variant was detected in a national registry of early\u2011onset hereditary ataxia in Iran, reinforcing its recurrence in A\u2011T cohorts [PMC10988936]. In a Japanese case\u2011control series, carriers of the truncating allele showed a markedly increased risk of mantle\u2011cell lymphoma, and the variant was listed among germline pathogenic ATM mutations [PMC9633290]. A large out\u2011of\u2011Africa DNA\u2011damage\u2011repair study also annotated c.829G>T as a pathogenic/likely\u2011pathogenic allele, noting its rarity in population databases [PMC11211533]. Homozygosity for the variant was reported in ataxia\u2011telangiectasia patients with class\u2011switch recombination defects, again supporting a pathogenic role [PMC8821084]. Cancer\u2011genome mining classified the mutation as \u201clikely oncogenic\u201d in uterine endometrioid carcinoma [PMC7979806] and a systematic review of bladder\u2011cancer association studies confirmed its pathogenic/likely\u2011pathogenic status in that disease context [PMC9931534].\nFunctional data are limited. One comprehensive colorectal\u2011cancer genomic profiling effort recorded the variant as a stop\u2011gain but did not provide experimental validation of its impact on ATM function [PMC9685809].\nPopulation\u2011level information indicates that the allele is extremely rare in reference cohorts (allele frequency reported as 0.00000\u20130.00133) [PMC9633290], consistent with a deleterious mutation. An endometrial\u2011cancer cohort reported a high intra\u2011cohort frequency (37.24%) of the variant, reflecting enrichment in that tumour type rather than a benign polymorphism [PMC11414036]. Computational modelling of the truncated protein structure in the Iranian case report suggested loss of critical domains, aligning with a loss\u2011of\u2011function mechanism [32962506].\nAcross the available literature there is no report describing the c.829G>T change as benign or of uncertain significance; all clinical classifications converge on a pathogenic interpretation. The convergence of multiple independent case reports, cancer\u2011risk association studies, rarity in the general population, and structural modelling collectively support the conclusion that ATM c.829G>T (p.Glu277Ter) is a pathogenic, loss\u2011of\u2011function variant.",
    "structured_summary": {
        "overall_pathogenicity": "pathogenic",
        "pathogenicity_counts": {
            "supports pathogenicity": 6,
            "uncertain": 0,
